english:
  title: The Military Governor
  author: Lee Ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    October frost descends on sea and sky,
    Leaves scatter—a thousand hills grow thin and bare.
    The general rides out at dawn on spirited steeds,
    Turquoise bow upon his arm, white plumes at his waist.
    Hawks soar fiercely, their cries sharp and shrill,
    Commands fall strict—his men seal their lips in silence.
    A painted horn sounds from the heavens above,
    And soldiers scatter like tigers, following his gesture.
    Mountains ringed, marshes enclosed, nowhere to hide,
    Hunt-fires blaze upward, arrows fall thick as rain.
    An ancient boar, thousand winters old, staggers and falls,
    It bounds five paces, then collapses after ten.
    Deer trapped, foxes cornered, wolves lie in heaps,
    Arrow-blood spatters, grass trampled and soaked.
    In a moment, mountains of prey pile high,
    A single dawn's catch—enough to exhaust all counting.
    The general turns in his saddle with laughter,
    The great banner ripples as the sun descends.
    After the offering to heaven, provisions are made,
    What remains is divided among the troops to feast.
    Here before my eyes is the deed of a true man,
    All voices cry out—nothing like it in ages past!
    A small scholar in the mountains, witnessing this,
    Wishes to write it down, but finds no room left on the page.
  footnotes:
    - The 'painted horn' (畫角) is a military instrument that signals the hunt's beginning.
    - The final image of the scholar unable to fit his account on one page is a playful commentary on the grandeur of the general's achievement—its magnitude exceeds what mere paper can contain.
